## Build & publish

```bash
make gen-key      # one-time: create the ed25519 publisher key (gitignored)
make package      # build -> sha256-pin -> sign manifest -> tarball
make publish-help # print the exact release + catalogue-PR steps
```

The signed bundle (`{{.ID}}-<version>.tar.gz`) is released on
`pilot-protocol/catalog`; a one-line entry in `catalogue/catalogue.json` on
`TeoSlayer/pilotprotocol@main` (via PR) makes it installable.

## Install & use

```bash
pilotctl appstore install {{.ID}}
pilotctl appstore call {{.ID}} {{.Namespace}}.help '{}'
{{- with index .Methods 0}}
pilotctl appstore call {{$.ID}} {{.Name}} '{}'
{{- end}}
```

The app ships pointing at production — no config step. To use a self-hosted
backend, drop `~/.pilot/apps/{{.ID}}/config.json` (`{"backend_url":"..."}`) and
`pilotctl appstore restart {{.ID}}`.

## Regenerating

Edit `pilot.app.yaml` and re-run `pilot-app init`. `cmd/`, `internal/backend/`,
`manifest.json`, and `metadata.json` are generated — keep changes in the spec,
not the code. Secrets are never committed: drop API keys in `secrets.json`
(gitignored) or the environment; `${TOKEN}` headers resolve them at runtime.
Bump `app_version` in the spec for every new binary.
